[1] Viet Nam
Date: Mon 14 Feb 2005
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: VOV News, 14 Feb 2005 [edited]
<http://www.vov.org.vn/2005_02_14/english/xahoi.htm#Seven%20provinces%20set%20for%20bird%20flu%20free%20status>


7 provinces set for bird flu free status
-----------------------------------------
No new bird flu outbreaks have been reported in 7 provinces in the
past 3 weeks across the country, namely Ha Nam, Binh Phuoc, Ninh
Binh, Kien Giang, Ninh Thuan, Lam Dong and Ho Chi Minh City,
according to the Veterinary Department.

The department said on Sunday [13 Feb 2005] that the provinces of Ha
Nam (in the north) and Binh Phuoc (in the south) have reported no new
outbreaks for a month.

However, it said the disease still broke out on a scattered basis in
some localities, with the latest outbreaks reported in Long An, Bac
Lieu, Hai Duong, Hai Phong and Long An. Nearly 7000 chickens, ducks
and quail have been culled. The department warned that the increasing
demand for the transport of chickens during the Tet holiday posed a
high risk for the transmission of the virus.

Meanwhile, all H5N1 patients and those who were suspected of
contracting the lethal virus were discharged from tropical disease
hospitals in Hanoi and Ho Chi Minh City before the traditional Lunar
New Year Festival (Tet) on 9 Feb 2005. They all showed positive signs
of recovery. Dr. Nguyen Duc Hien, head of the National Institute for
Tropical Diseases, said experts from the World Health Organization
(WHO) will arrive in Viet Nam to study the transmission mechanism of
bird flu from chickens to humans. WHO will also study the production
of preventive vaccines in case the virus strain changes.

